>it just feels like there's a colossal divide between those characteristics that impose inhibitions on men and women.
Not going to argue the point one bit, here, but you need to remember that you don't have to approach things from the same direction to have the same goal or for struggles to fall into the same category. To go with a simple example, girls tend to worry about weight, while guys tend to worry about strength and body composition. Another example would be social graces. Guys and girls climb the social ladder through completely different means, but they both want to climb, and trying new things socially is the best way to get good at this quickly. You don't need to match, just compliment.

> I want to be a better man before I even try to find somebody.
Dude, you're pre baking a loaf of excuses and wrapping it in a noble notion. The act of improving your social skills to the point where you can find Mrs. Anon's waifu is part of self improvement as well.

> I don't want to disappoint anyone
Tough shit. It's part of growing, and a painful one at that. There's nothing wrong with wanting to avoid it, but you can't let that paralyze you. If you never do anything, you'll never be on anyone's radar enough to disappoint them. ...until you realize that you're disappointing yourself.

Anonymous Fri 09 Nov 2018 22:05:46 No.19322258 Report
Quoted By: >>19322311 >>19322664 >>19340181
>>19321895
1/2

The skeleton and painting are by artist Bonnie Dalzell, for an unpublished SF art book from the 70s. Supposedly both were approved by Larry Niven--and if anyone knows what Kzinti are supposed to look like, it's him.

Cover artists have drawn a lot of furry bait cover art for the various Man-Kzin Wars anthologies that Baen has been publishing irregularly for 25+ years.

And no, Kzinti aren't supposed to be vertebrates. They're mammal-ish, with a bony skeleton, but their skeletons are constructed very unlike any Earthly life, and they have no true spinal column. But that cage of bone supporting the torso is very tough and contains lots of redundancies.

Supposedly the Kzinti were apex predators of a hot arid, high-gravity world with life generally being much more vigorous than Earth's, and were evolved to the point where they would probably have been making tools in another half million years when an unknown alien race happened upon them and genetically engineered them into enthusiastic soldier-bodyguards. The aliens were promptly overthrown and eaten by the Kzinti, who found themselves surrounded by technology they did not create and do not fully understand. They did figure out genetic engineering, though, and used it to make themselves into their equivalent of the Ubermensch, giving themselves traits of the gods and heroes of their legends, not knowing or not caring that it was their alien benefactors who created these legends for them in the first place. Their females had been uplifted to sentience with them, but Kzinti males don't like opinionated females and made them nonsentient again. So, we have modern starfaring Kzinti, two to two and a half meters tall, 250+ kg and almost all of it muscle, short-tempered and aggressive. They're not at all stupid, but they genetically hardwired themselves in a way that leaves them not good at strategy, or tactics more complex than "scream and leap."

2/2

The Kzinti keep losing these wars, and humanity keeps stopping short of exterminating them entirely, so they happen again and again at regular intervals. One of the results, though, is that the Kzinti, despite their self-imposed instinctive programming, are getting smarter and smarter, as only the very brightest of them survive each time humanity comes a-calling. And they're starting to figure out that scream-and-leap tactics don't lend themselves to interstellar warfare. A few of them are even beginning to question a religion that tells them that all other sentient life in the universe is either slaves or food for them.

Anyway. The Kzinti are enormous, muscular, evolved in a 1.8G environment, short-tempered, and a bit dumb, as well as spectacularly ugly. This is many things but it ain't sexy.

A fanfiction writer back around 1990 wrote an erotic story involving a human and an adolescent female Kzin whom he had raised from a cub.

Niven wasn't amused, and sued, mainly because his name was splashed all over it as it was even then spread worldwide over the (colleges and universities only, UNIX command line prompt) Internet, and he, understandably, did not want his name associated with "Loli Catgirls in Space" stuff.

As far as i remember the Kzinti were farther along their cultural development.

They were about bronze ageish. Anyways the aliens who decided to uplift them (the Jotoki) found out that its not too smart to try to uplift big territorial carnivores with a strong social hierarchy.

Anyways after a quick bit of conquest and enslavement the victorius Kzin returned home and decided to make their mythical heroes real. And real Kzin heroes were big straightforward dudes that did not lie or skulk about but punched motherfuckers in the face if they needed a good punching. And there were a lot of motherfuckers needing a good punching.

And real Kzin females should keep their mouth shut and stay in the bedroom. Helpfully genetic engineering had the solution to these issues.

Kzinti being stupid berserkers is somewhat inflated inuniverse. They are in general more impulsive and brutish than humans. But a lot of their scream-kill-maybe-think-later reputation is because the first world of theirs that came aware of humanity was a small, crowded, barely habitable world filled primarily with the chaff of their species.

So when they heard of a bunch of presumably helpless monkeys that had colonized several garden worlds they all jumped into their ships and decided get rich or die trying.

The two first wars was basically Kzin hillbillies just grabbing their shotguns and piling into their pickup trucks. The next war had a actual Kzin warlord taking control but he got assassinated and then all the hillbillies started fighting each other for the privilege of becoming the next warlord.

Then the humans turned up in their hyperdrive capable ships that they had gotten off the Outsiders who were led to humanity by the Pierson`s Puppeteers.

...Come to think of it Humanity got off easy.

Pierson's Puppeteers are about as harmless-looking as a sentient species can be and they cultivate that reputation. No one takes them seriously. They're wealthy from trade, and tremendously technologically advanced, but cowardly.

And they pulled strings in the background to start most of the wars in the galaxy in the last several thousand years.

Humans, being warlike, scared them. The Kzinti scared them just as much, if not more. They decided to put the two species in a jar, shake 'em up, and see if they could get them to fight, preferably to mutual extermination.

When humanity got the upper hand--the early stuff was pretty clearly in HFY territory--the Puppeteers decided that of the two they would rather attempt to coexist with humans in the near term, and arranged matters so that humanity got faster-than-light travel from the Outsiders.

There's more going on the background. A total energy conversion powerplant experiment belonging to the Puppeteers got out of hand in the galactic core and set off the nearest several suns as supernovae--in a part of the galaxy where stars are only a few light-months apart. A tsunami supernova chain reaction is spreading out of the galactic core at just under lightspeed. It will reach the portion of the galaxy that humans and Kzinti inhabit in about twenty thousand years. The Puppeteers have already loaded up their civilization on five planets, complete with artificial suns, and are headed for Andromeda at relativistic speeds. They're so scared of something that won't get here for twenty thousand years that they are moving an entire solar system. Oh, and they haven't told anyone else "oops, we blew up the galaxy" yet, because all their neighbors are going to be PISSED.
